Growth has slowed to a crawl at 25,600, so in order to get above 40k we'd need a 15k+ wave in the next 45 days. The first wave took two months to get to15k, so getting to 40k would require a wave that was immediate and more intense, I'm assigning at <0.5%.

As of now, there are 25,509 total cases of monkeypox in the US with California being the state with the most cases. Daily US infections now average around 200 after peaking at around 450 in mid-August according to the Washington Post. Monkeypox would only become a bigger threat if it spreads to wild animal populations like it did in Africa. We are also more aware as a society of what to do about pandemics and epidemics because of COVID, making everyone more cautious than we would be normally. With the daily average being around 200, by November 18th there should be around 10,000 new cases give or take assuming that cases won’t dramatically increase or decrease. This makes the confirmed cases pretty far under 40,000 when November 18th rolls around.
Crossed 25k today but things are slowing to ~1k per week with 6 weeks left, seems we'll be finishing in the 25-40k bucket unless there is a huge superspreader event.

The U.S. has the largest number of confirmed cases of Monkeypox of any countries, with a Monkeypox vaccine yet to be administered to the general public. However, the number of confirmed cases per day is slowly decreasing.

+52% to 25-40k, -6% to 40-55k, -30% to 55-70k, -7% to 70-85k, -5% to 85-100k, -3% to 100-115k, -1% to 115-130k. Big adjustment. The 7-day average is currently 324/day (~44.5k by Nov 11th). And the trend is downward dropping from 520/day just 3 weeks ago.

45k was my last weighted estimate. I weighed a scenario where weekly cases continue to drop and a scenario where weekly cases return to the ascent, giving more weight to the former scenario of cases continuing to decline. Adjusting a bit more based on other forecasters' forecasts.
Its trailing off quite quickly now. If there were 12,000 cases in August and there will be fewer in Sept and Oct, then its not possible for the total to get above 40,000.
Case growth has been flat for about a month. Small upticks or downticks all result in somewhere between 25-70k

Setting a base rate. Assuming that the daily growth will continue to slow(from 500/day currently). So, maybe 350 per day average case rate for the next 80 days. Roughly 50K cases. 80% allocated to 40-70K seems reasonable, that is between 280 and 650 cases per day on average. If the daily pace continues to slow i will consolidate my forecast in that range...risk is that cases start flaring up again.

I used my two old prophet methods to predict this one. One bases on the daily total cases and the other on daily new cases. Facebook Prophet takes those time series data and makes a projection. The first one predicts 48974 - 63217. The second predicts a value around 78993. They lead me to my first forecast.
